00:23:42,420 --> 00:23:44,000
Scott: But yeah, you cannot speak Ewok.

465
00:23:44,220 --> 00:23:46,040
Scott: That is not a fully fleshed out language.

466
00:23:46,620 --> 00:23:50,600
Rym: So, my thing of the day is very much related to the topic at hand and to my news.

467
00:23:50,880 --> 00:23:53,759
Rym: You see, all three of my things are in fact the same thing.

468
00:23:54,060 --> 00:23:54,151
Scott: Snow.

469
00:23:54,321 --> 00:23:56,600
Scott: Oh my god, is there a word for that when all three things match?

470
00:23:57,241 --> 00:23:58,956
Rym: Well, you see- A trifecta?

471
00:23:59,280 --> 00:24:04,537
Rym: The word used on Fark is trifecta, which apparently is a term from horse racing when a very specific thing happens.

472
00:24:05,481 --> 00:24:12,902
Rym: But on Fark, a trifecta is when three stories that are far too related to be normally statistically probable, like

473
00:24:13,223 --> 00:24:13,483
Scott: say

474
00:24:13,724 --> 00:24:24,639
Rym: there are two stories of fat people exploding, then people start posting in the end of the second one, "Man, if there's a trifecta of this, I'm buying a lottery

475
00:24:24,659 --> 00:24:24,800
Rym: ticket.".

476
00:24:26,047 --> 00:24:26,618
Scott: I would too.

477
00:24:27,060 --> 00:24:28,918
